The Hadamard gate is perhaps the most important quantum gate because it is the standard way to create a superposition from a definite state. It is denoted by the letter H and is defined as:H = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 1 & -1 \end{pmatrix}

Why the factor of \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}? This normalisation factor ensures that the output states are properly normalised (have unit length). Without it, the probabilities wouldn’t add up to 1, which would violate the fundamental rules of quantum mechanics.

When applied to |0\rangle, the Hadamard gate creates an equal superposition:H|0\rangle = \frac{|0\rangle + |1\rangle}{\sqrt{2}}

This means if we measure the qubit, we have a 50% chance of getting 0 and a 50% chance of getting 1. It’s the quantum analogue of flipping a fair coin.

When applied to |1\rangle, it creates a different equal superposition:H|1\rangle = \frac{|0\rangle - |1\rangle}{\sqrt{2}}

Notice the minus sign in front of |1\rangle. This is not just a cosmetic difference — the minus sign represents a phase difference. In quantum mechanics, phase matters enormously. Two superpositions that look similar can have very different behaviours because of subtle phase differences. This is the source of quantum interference, which is exploited in quantum algorithms to amplify correct answers and cancel wrong ones.

The Heisenberg uncertainty principle is one of the most famous results in quantum mechanics. It states that certain pairs of physical properties, like position and momentum, cannot both be known to arbitrary precision:\Delta x \cdot \Delta p \geq \frac{\hbar}{2}

where \Delta x = \sqrt{\langle x^2 \rangle - \langle x \rangle^2} and \Delta p = \sqrt{\langle p^2 \rangle - \langle p \rangle^2} are the standard deviations (uncertainties).

For the particle in a box, we can compute both uncertainties and verify that their product satisfies the inequality.

Consider a particle of energy E incident on a finite potential barrier:V(x) = \begin{cases} 0 & x < 0 \\ V_0 & 0 \leq x \leq a \\ 0 & x > a \end{cases}

For E < V_0, the wave function in the barrier region (0 \leq x \leq a) satisfies:\frac{d^2\psi}{dx^2} = \frac{2m(V_0 - E)}{\hbar^2}\psi = \kappa^2 \psi

where \kappa = \sqrt{2m(V_0 - E)}/\hbar is real. The solution is:\psi(x) = Ae^{\kappa x} + Be^{-\kappa x}

The wave function decays exponentially inside the barrier rather than oscillating. If the barrier is thin enough, a non-zero amplitude survives to the other side — the particle “tunnels” through.

H = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 1 & -1 \end{pmatrix}

The Hadamard gate creates superpositions: H|0\rangle = \frac{|0\rangle + |1\rangle}{\sqrt{2}} = |+\rangle and H|1\rangle = \frac{|0\rangle - |1\rangle}{\sqrt{2}} = |-\rangle.

A key property: H^2 = I, meaning two Hadamard gates in sequence cancel out.
